(294, 0, '2016-07-26 09:49:04', '2016-07-26 09:49:04', 'Solution :\r\n<span>Migrations are like version control for your database, allowing a team to easily modify and share the application''s database schema. Migrations are typically paired with Laravel''s schema builder to easily build your application''s database schema.</span>\r\n<a href="https://laravel.com/docs/5.2/migrations#generating-migrations">Generating Migrations</a>\r\nTo create a migration, use the<code class=" language-php">make<span style="color: #999999">:</span>migration</code><a href="https://laravel.com/docs/5.2/artisan">Artisan command</a>:\r\n<pre><code class=" language-php">php artisan make<span style="color: #999999">:</span>migration create_users_table<br /><br /><span>The new migration will be placed in your</span><code class=" language-php">database<span style="color: #555555">/</span>migrations</code><span>directory. Each migration file name contains a timestamp which allows Laravel to determine the order of the migrations.</span><br /></code></pre>\r\n', 'How to create Migration file in laravel ?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'how-to-create-migration-file-in-laravel', '', '', '2016-07-26 09:52:33', '2016-07-26 09:52:33', '', 0, 'http://programmerlab.com/dwqa-question/how-to-create-migration-file-in-laravel/', 0, 'dwqa-question', '', 0),
(295, 0, '2016-07-26 09:52:32', '2016-07-26 09:52:32', 'The<code class=" language-php"><span style="color: #555555">--</span>table</code>and<code class=" language-php"><span style="color: #555555">--</span>create</code>options may also be used to indicate the name of the table and whether the migration will be creating a new table. These options simply pre-fill the generated migration stub file with the specified table:\r\n<pre><code class=" language-php"> php artisan make<span style="color: #999999">:</span>migration create_users_table <span style="color: #555555">--</span>create<span style="color: #555555">=</span>users</code></pre>', 'Answer for How to create Migration file in laravel ?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'answer-for-how-to-create-migration-file-in-laravel', '', '', '2016-07-26 09:52:32', '2016-07-26 09:52:32', '', 294, 'http://programmerlab.com/dwqa-answer/answer-for-how-to-create-migration-file-in-laravel/', 0, 'dwqa-answer', '', 0),
(296, 0, '2016-07-26 10:02:09', '2016-07-26 10:02:09', 'Solution :<br />Step1: Create Migration file<br />command :<span>php artisan make</span><span>:</span><span>migration create_admin_table </span><span>--</span><span>create</span><span>=</span><span>admin</span>\r\n<span>Step2: The new migration will be placed in your</span><code class=" language-php">database<span style="color: #555555">/</span>migrations</code><span>directory.</span>\r\nStep3: your migration file will look like following\r\n&lt;?php\r\n\r\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Schema\\Blueprint;\r\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Migrations\\Migration;\r\n\r\nclass CreateAdminTable extends Migration\r\n{\r\n  /**\r\n  * Run the migrations.\r\n  *\r\n  * @return void\r\n  */\r\n  public function up()\r\n  {\r\n    Schema::create(''admin'', function (Blueprint $table) {\r\n      $table-&gt;increments(''id'');\r\n      $table-&gt;string(''email'');\r\n      $table-&gt;password(''password'');\r\n      $table-&gt;timestamps();\r\n    });\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  /**\r\n  * Reverse the migrations.\r\n  *\r\n  * @return void\r\n  */\r\n  public function down()\r\n  {\r\n    Schema::drop(''admin'');\r\n  }\r\n}\r\nYou can add you new field as per requirement.\r\nStep4: Go to terminal and run\r\nphp artisan migrate\r\n<span>If you receive a "class not found" error when running migrations, try running the</span><code class=" language-php">composer dump<span style="color: #555555">-</span>autoload</code><span>command and re-issuing the migrate command.</span>', 'How to create table using migration  in laravel with example?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'how-to-create-table-using-migration-in-laravel-with-example', '', '', '2016-07-26 10:02:09', '2016-07-26 10:02:09', '', 0, 'http://programmerlab.com/dwqa-question/how-to-create-table-using-migration-in-laravel-with-example/', 0, 'dwqa-question', '', 0),
(297, 0, '2016-07-26 10:28:54', '2016-07-26 10:28:54', 'Solution :\r\n<span>To generate a seeder, you may issue the</span><code class=" language-php">make<span style="color: #999999">:</span>seeder</code><span></span><a href="https://laravel.com/docs/5.2/artisan">Artisan command</a><span>. All seeders generated by the framework will be placed in the</span><code class=" language-php">database<span style="color: #555555">/</span>seeds</code><span>directory:</span>\r\nStep1: Suppose you want to create seeder for admin table then\r\n<pre><code class=" language-php">php artisan make<span style="color: #999999">:</span>seeder AdminTableSeeder</code></pre>\r\nstep2: after running abovecommand you will see a file will be created in<code class=" language-php">database<span style="color: #555555">/</span>seeds</code><span> directory</span>\r\nStep3: Open this file and file will look like following\r\n&lt;?php\r\nuse Illuminate\\Database\\Seeder;\r\nclass AdminTableSeeder extends Seeder\r\n{\r\n  /**\r\n  * Run the database seeds.\r\n  *\r\n  * @return void\r\n  */\r\n  public function run()\r\n  {\r\n    DB::table(''admin'')-&gt;insert([\r\n      ''email'' =&gt; ''admin@udex.com'',\r\n      ''password'' =&gt; bcrypt(''admin''),\r\n    ]);\r\n  }\r\n}\r\nStep4: you can put value as per your requirement\r\n\r\n DB::table(''admin'')-&gt;insert([\r\n      ''email'' =&gt; ''admin@udex.com'',\r\n      ''password'' =&gt; bcrypt(''admin''),\r\n    ]);\r\nstep5: Run following command.\r\n\r\nphp artisan db:seed --class=AdminTableSeeder\r\nThanks :)\r\n', 'How to create Database  Seeding in laravel ?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'how-to-create-database-seeding-in-laravel', '', '', '2016-07-26 10:28:54', '2016-07-26 10:28:54', '', 0, 'http://programmerlab.com/dwqa-question/how-to-create-database-seeding-in-laravel/', 0, 'dwqa-question', '', 0),
