(422, 1, '2017-02-23 15:48:10', '2017-02-23 15:48:10', '<p><strong>Step 1:</strong>Login to your server via SSH as root user.<br />\n<strong>Step 2:</strong>Open the CSF configuration file (/etc/csf/csf.conf) with your favourite editor and search the directive PT_USERMEM.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<pre><code class="hljs nginx">nano /etc/csf/csf.conf</code></pre>\n<p>Set the value of PT_USERMEM to 0 to disable this feature from CSF (see below).</p>\n<pre><code class="hljs nginx"># This User Process Tracking option sends an alert if any cPanel user process\r\n# exceeds the memory usage set (MB). To ignore specific processes or users use\r\n# csf.pignore\r\n# \r\n# Set to 0 to disable this feature\r\n\r\n PT_USERMEM = "0"</code></pre>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>And then restart CSF</p>\n<pre><code class="hljs nginx">csf -r</code></pre>\n</blockquote>\n', 'How to disable Lfd excessive resource usage alert?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'how-to-disable-lfd-excessive-resource-usage-alert', '', '', '2017-02-23 15:48:36', '2017-02-23 15:48:36', '', 0, 'http://programmerlab.com/question/how-to-disable-lfd-excessive-resource-usage-alert/', 0, 'dwqa-question', '', 0),
